<subSubSection pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
121. 
<taxonomicName LSID="38753F42-7E85-5175-8F97-D4EC2347C0F3" authority="(Vved.) Petrov, Byull. Moskovsk. Obshch. Isp. Prir., Otd. Biol., n. ser., 44: 132. 1935. (Petrov 1935: 132)." authorityName="Petrov, Byull. Moskovsk. Obshch. Isp. Prir., Otd. Biol., n. ser., 44: 132. 1935. (Petrov" authorityYear="1935" baseAuthorityName="Vved." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus hamadae" order="Solanales" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hamadae">Convolvulus hamadae (Vved.) Petrov, Byull. Moskovsk. Obshch. Isp. Prir., Otd. Biol., n.ser., 44: 132. 1935. (Petrov 1935: 132).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vvedensky" authorityYear="1927" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus subsericeus subsp. hamadae" order="Solanales" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="subsericeus" subSpecies="hamadae">Convolvulus subsericeus subsp. hamadae</taxonomicName>
Vved., Byull. Sredne-Aziatsk. Gosud. Univ. 15 (Suppl.): 32. 1927. (
<bibRefCitation author="Popov, MG" journalOrPublisher="Biulleten Sredne-Aziatskogo Gosudarstvennogo Universiteta Tashkent" pageId="209" pageNumber="210" pagination="s 1 - s 53" refId="B283" refString="Popov, MG, Vvedensky, AI, 1927. Schedae ad Herbarium Florae Asiae Mediae, fasc. 11-13. Biulleten Sredne-Aziatskogo Gosudarstvennogo Universiteta Tashkent 15: s1 - s53" title="Schedae ad Herbarium Florae Asiae Mediae, fasc. 11 - 13" volume="15" year="1927">Popov and Vvedensky 1927</bibRefCitation>
: 32). Type. KAZAKHSTAN, Kara-tau, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Popov</emphasis>
5/6/1926 (holotype TAK; isotypes B, BM!, E!, K!, LE!, P!, W!.)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="type">
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
Based on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vvedensky" authorityYear="1927" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus subsericeus subsp. hamadae" order="Solanales" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="subsericeus" subSpecies="hamadae">Convolvulus subsericeus subsp. hamadae</taxonomicName>
Vved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
Erect undershrub, intricately branched from the base to at least 40 cm; stems, thinly sericeous. Leaves 1-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2 cm, linear-oblong, acute, base tapering into a long pseudopetiole, thinly adpressed pubescent and appearing greenish. Flowers 1 (-2) at the apex of rigid, straight, relatively slender woody peduncles 0.8-1.5 cm long; bracteoles minute, linear, c. 1 mm, pedicels 0.5-1 mm, bent at 90° to peduncle; sepals (3-) 4 (-5) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5 mm, narrowly oblong, acute, densely pubescent; corolla (8-)10 mm, white, unlobed, broadly infundibuliform, midpetaline bands pilose, terminating in a tooth; ovary pilose. Capsule pilose, seeds pubescent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="144" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="143" pageNumber="144" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="143" pageNumber="144">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="144" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="143" pageNumber="144">
Kazakhstan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<pageBreakToken pageId="144" pageNumber="145" start="start">Drobov</pageBreakToken>
</emphasis>
s.n. [3/8/1996], 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Krasheninnikov</emphasis>
158); Kyrgyzstan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Knorring</emphasis>
115, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Drobov</emphasis>
246); Uzbekistan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Tishchenko</emphasis>
98, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Muravliansky</emphasis>
1932, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Knorring</emphasis>
60); Tajikistan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Nikitin</emphasis>
167, s.n. [19/6/1936], 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Knorring</emphasis>
129); Turkmenistan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Litvinow</emphasis>
1647, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Sintenis</emphasis>
1285); Afghanistan (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Aitchison</emphasis>
731); Iran (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Pabot</emphasis>
DK 518). Most common in Uzbekistan.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="144" pageNumber="145" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
The indumentum and corolla size suggests this lies between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ledeb., in Eichwald, Pl. Nov. Cauc. Casp. 11. 1831. (Eichwald" authorityYear="1831" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus erinaceus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erinaceus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus erinaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrenk, Enum. Pl. Nov. [F. E. L. Fischer &amp; C. A. Meyer] 1: 19. 1841. (Fischer and Meyer" authorityYear="1841" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus subsericeus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericeus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus subsericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or more probably 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss. &amp; Buhse, Nouv. Mem. Soc. Imp. Naturalises Moscou 12: 148. 1860. (Boissier and Buhse" authorityYear="1860" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus eremophilus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="eremophilus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus eremophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, given the distribution of the three species. It has a laxer, less rigid appearance than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ledeb., in Eichwald, Pl. Nov. Cauc. Casp. 11. 1831. (Eichwald" authorityYear="1831" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus erinaceus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erinaceus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus erinaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with branches less divaricate, the corolla is longer and unlobed and the sepals are acute, not obtuse. From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrenk, Enum. Pl. Nov. [F. E. L. Fischer &amp; C. A. Meyer] 1: 19. 1841. (Fischer and Meyer" authorityYear="1841" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus subsericeus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="subsericeus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus subsericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is distinguished by the shorter, pungent branches, flowers generally solitary and a little smaller, the sepals acute, not acuminate. From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boiss. &amp; Buhse, Nouv. Mem. Soc. Imp. Naturalises Moscou 12: 148. 1860. (Boissier and Buhse" authorityYear="1860" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus eremophilus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="eremophilus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus eremophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is distinguished by the sparse, adpressed indumentum of the stems and shorter corolla. A few specimens are completely glabrous, such as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Botchantzev</emphasis>
468 from Uzbekistan, but seem to fit here best.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="144" pageNumber="145">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
treated this species as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ledeb., in Eichwald, Pl. Nov. Cauc. Casp. 11. 1831. (Eichwald" authorityYear="1831" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus erinaceus" order="Solanales" pageId="144" pageNumber="145" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erinaceus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="145">Convolvulus erinaceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the sepals and corolla are quite different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
